  "source": "Obstentrics_Williams_textbook_data.txt: Back pain is one of the most common complaints during pregnancy, affecting 50-70% of pregnant women. The most common type is pregnancy-related low back pain, which typically affects the lumbar region, often radiating to the posterior thighs. It is associated with increased lumbar lordosis (swayback) secondary to the enlarging uterus and anterior shift in the body's center of gravity. Pelvic girdle pain is another common type, affecting the sacroiliac joints and pubic symphysis. Risk factors include previous episodes of back pain, multiparty, increased maternal weight, and physically demanding work. Physiological changes contributing to back pain during pregnancy include weight gain, postural changes, hormonal effects (particularly relaxin, which increases ligamentous laxity), and mechanical stress on the sacroiliac joints and pelvic ligaments. Management primarily involves activity modification, appropriate exercises, pelvic support belts, physical therapy, and acetaminophen for pain relief. Most pregnancy-related back pain resolves after delivery, although some women may experience persistent symptoms.",
