  "source": "Surgery_Schwartz_textbook_data.txt: Cauda equina syndrome is a neurosurgical emergency characterized by compression of the cauda equina (the bundle of nerve roots descending from the lower spinal cord). It typically presents with a characteristic constellation of symptoms including saddle anesthesia (numbness in the perineal region), bowel and/or bladder dysfunction (urinary retention, overflow incontinence, or fecal incontinence), bilateral radicular pain, and lower extremity weakness. The most common cause is a large central disc herniation, though other causes include trauma, tumor, epidural hematoma, or abscess. MRI is the diagnostic modality of choice. Treatment consists of urgent surgical decompression, ideally within 48 hours of symptom onset. Delay in diagnosis and treatment may result in permanent neurological deficits, particularly bladder and bowel dysfunction. Prognosis depends largely on the severity and duration of symptoms before decompression, with better outcomes observed in patients who undergo surgery within 24-48 hours of symptom onset.",
