  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Fibromyalgia is a central pain syndrome characterized by chronic widespread musculoskeletal pain, fatigue, sleep disturbances, and cognitive dysfunction. It affects approximately 2-4% of the population, with a female-to-male ratio of 7:1. The 2016 diagnostic criteria from the American College of Rheumatology include: (1) widespread pain index (WPI) ≥7 and symptom severity scale (SSS) score ≥5, or WPI 4-6 and SSS ≥9; (2) symptoms present at a similar level for at least 3 months; and (3) no other disorder that would otherwise explain the pain. Common associated symptoms include cognitive difficulties ('fibro fog'), headaches, irritable bowel symptoms, and paresthesias. Physical examination typically reveals multiple tender points, though these are no longer required for diagnosis. Many patients with fibromyalgia report sicca symptoms (dry eyes, dry mouth) similar to those seen in Sjögren's syndrome, with prevalence rates of 20-35% for sicca-like symptoms in fibromyalgia cohorts. The pathophysiology involves central sensitization with amplification of pain transmission and decreased descending inhibition of pain pathways.",
