  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Mechanical low back pain, including lumbar strain or sprain, accounts for approximately 70% of all low back pain cases. It typically results from overuse, improper use, or trauma to the paraspinal, lumbar, and abdominal muscles and/or ligaments. Clinically, patients present with acute-onset pain localized to the lower back, often after a specific inciting event such as heavy lifting or twisting. The pain is exacerbated by movement and may be associated with muscle spasm and reduced range of motion. Unlike radicular pain, mechanical back pain does not radiate below the buttocks, and neurological examination remains normal. The straight leg raise test is typically negative. Muscle spasm and localized tenderness of the affected muscles are often present on examination. Most cases are self-limited, with significant improvement within 2-4 weeks with conservative management.",
